strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2017-02-15T16:33:22.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685397/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685397/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685397/answer",,,,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-02-06","Attorney General: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many security passes into the Law Officers' Departments are issued to people (a) not directly employed by and (b) who are not civil servants who work in the Law Officers' Departments.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","63255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685398","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-14","<p>The Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman is independent of Government. It publishes information on staffing and its performance in its Annual Report and Resource Accounts which are laid before Parliament. Operational decisions on the location of PHSO offices are also matters for the Ombudsman and the Hon. Member should write to the Ombudsman on these matters.</p><p>The Government published the draft Public Service Ombudsman Bill in December 2016, setting out in detail its plans to introduce a new Public Service Ombudsman. The proposals contained in the draft Bill seek to bring together the responsibilities of the current Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman and the Local Government Ombudsman to create a new organisation with strengthened governance and accountability. The Government intends to introduce the Bill when parliamentary time allows. A copy of the draft Bill has been placed in the Library of the House and it can also be accessed at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/draft-public-service-ombudsman-bill" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/draft-public-service-ombudsman-bill</a></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","63236 ; 63237","2017-02-14T11:03:58.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685398/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685398/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685398/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-06","Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many cases accepted for investigation by the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman were classed as open in each month since January 2015.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","63235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685399","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-14","<p>As at the 31<sup>st</sup> of December 2016, the number of Building Access (security) passes issued by the Cabinet Office to people (a) not directly employed by and (b) who are not civil servants and who work or regularly visit the Cabinet Office was 39. The numbers of such passes will fluctuate over the course of a year.</p><p>Such passes are issued to contractors, secondees, other public sector workers or Crown Servant (such as the police or military forces) as well as to civil servants where it is necessary and appropriate to do so. This enables teams to work flexibly and effectively and best support the business need. The use of all such passes is underpinned by a strong physical security focus, access to control procedures and technologies, clear processes and assurance mechanisms that enable an integrated work force to operate in a secure manner.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-02-14T15:08:41.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685399/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685399/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685399/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-06","Cabinet Office: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many security passes into his Department are issued to people (a) not directly employed by and (b) who are not civil servants who work in his Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","63256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685400","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-09","<p>I refer My Rt. Hon Friend to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Hemsworth on 7 February 2017 to UIN: 62923.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-02-09T13:16:56.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685400/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685400/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685400/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-06","Capita: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which contracts the Government has awarded to Capita in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","63305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685401","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-14","<p>The Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman is independent of Government. It publishes information on staffing and its performance in its Annual Report and Resource Accounts which are laid before Parliament. Operational decisions on the location of PHSO offices are also matters for the Ombudsman and the Hon. Member should write to the Ombudsman on these matters.</p><p>The Government published the draft Public Service Ombudsman Bill in December 2016, setting out in detail its plans to introduce a new Public Service Ombudsman. The proposals contained in the draft Bill seek to bring together the responsibilities of the current Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman and the Local Government Ombudsman to create a new organisation with strengthened governance and accountability. The Government intends to introduce the Bill when parliamentary time allows. A copy of the draft Bill has been placed in the Library of the House and it can also be accessed at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/draft-public-service-ombudsman-bill" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/draft-public-service-ombudsman-bill</a></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","63235 ; 63237","2017-02-14T11:03:58.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685401/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685401/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685401/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-06","Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether his Department plans to move any of the operations carried out by the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman outside of London.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","63236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685402","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-14","<p>The Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman is independent of Government. It publishes information on staffing and its performance in its Annual Report and Resource Accounts which are laid before Parliament. Operational decisions on the location of PHSO offices are also matters for the Ombudsman and the Hon. Member should write to the Ombudsman on these matters.</p><p>The Government published the draft Public Service Ombudsman Bill in December 2016, setting out in detail its plans to introduce a new Public Service Ombudsman. The proposals contained in the draft Bill seek to bring together the responsibilities of the current Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman and the Local Government Ombudsman to create a new organisation with strengthened governance and accountability. The Government intends to introduce the Bill when parliamentary time allows. A copy of the draft Bill has been placed in the Library of the House and it can also be accessed at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/draft-public-service-ombudsman-bill" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/draft-public-service-ombudsman-bill</a></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","63235 ; 63236","2017-02-14T11:03:58.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685402/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685402/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-06","Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether his Department plans to converge services undertaken by the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman with the Local Government Ombudsman.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","63237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685403","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-14","<p>Investment decisions within the Parliamentary Contributory Pensions Fund, including consideration of risks arising from investments in the fossil fuel extractive industry, are a matter for the Trustees who receive professional advice regarding decisions about the management of scheme assets.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-02-14T09:48:29.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685403/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685403/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-06","Parliamentary Contributory Pension Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 3 February 2017 to Question 61923, what assessment he has made of the long-term risks to the financial performance of the Parliamentary Contributory Pensions Fund of that funds' investments in the fossil fuel extractive industry.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","63244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685404","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-14","<p>Since the beginning of December 2016, the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) has launched no cost marketing activities to publicise the vehicle excise duty (VED) rates, which will apply to vehicles first registered from 1 April 2017. The campaign aimed towards the general public is being run across social media and is supported by messages on DVLA literature. The DVLA and HM Treasury are also engaging with vehicle manufacturers to encourage them to raise awareness with their retailers and customers on the impact of the changes.</p><p> </p><p>This initial campaign is being supported by paid for publicity activity to target potential new car buyers in the run up to 1 April 2017. This will include messages on internet search engines and on key motor trade websites. The planned cost is up to £95,000 including VAT; £8,000 was spent on the first phase in January. All communications point to a page on GOV.UK (<a href="http://www.gov.uk/newvehicletaxrates" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/newvehicletaxrates</a>) which gives further detail of the changes.</p><p> </p><p>Any paid for communications activity costing over £100,000 would be subject to central government spend controls.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-14T16:09:46.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685404/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685404/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-06","Motor Vehicles: Tax Rates and Bands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency's news story of 30 January 2017, new vehicle tax rate from 1 April 2017, what steps his Department and Cabinet colleagues are taking to raise awareness of those new vehicle tax rates; and what the cost to the public purse of publicising those new rates will be.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","63243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685405","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-13","<p>The Government believes in making the most of the UK’s oil and gas resources. The oil and gas industry has contributed around £330bn to the Exchequer to date, supports hundreds of thousands of jobs and supplies a large proportion of the UK’s primary energy needs.</p><p> </p><p>Decommissioning is an inherent cost of doing business in the UK Continental Shelf, as companies are required by law to decommission oil and gas infrastructure after production ceases. Estimates of the total cost of decommissioning vary, due to the complexity of work and long timeframes involved. HM Revenue and Customs’ Annual Report and Accounts 2014-15 estimates that, out of a total of £41bn decommissioning costs between 2015 and 2041, the Exchequer’s share is £16bn. This is due to repayments through decommissioning tax relief, which are only made if tax has been paid in the first place.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to ensuring decommissioning programmes represent value for money, as this delivers benefits both to industry and the Exchequer. The Maximising Economic Recovery UK Strategy places an obligation on oil and gas licensees to decommission assets in the most cost-effective way, ensuring all viable options for the continued use of that infrastructure have been considered. The Government has given the Oil and Gas Authority (OGA) a new remit to work with industry on cost reduction and delivery capability for decommissioning. The OGA also has a duty to advise the Secretary of State for the Department of Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy on the cost effectiveness of decommissioning programmes.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-13T12:41:47.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685405/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685405/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-06","Offshore Industry: Decommissioning","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the cost of decommissioning North Sea oil infrastructure; for what proportion of those costs the taxpayer will be liable; and what steps he plans to take to reduce those costs.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","63179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685406","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-09","<p>HM Treasury receives a wide range of representations on the future of vehicle taxation, including on the VED reforms that are due to come into force in April 2017. Recent representations from the British Vehicle Rental and Leasing Association (BVRLA) and some of its members covered the issues set out in this question.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-09T15:52:03.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685406/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685406/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-06","Motor Vehicles: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has received representations on his proposed change to vehicle taxation scheduled for April 2017 on (a) the potential effect on future vehicles, (b) the potential effect on air quality and (c) postponing the introduction of those changes until further consultation is carried out.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","63203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685407","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-13","<p>No estimate has been made of the cost of abolishing employer National Insurance contributions for care leavers. An estimate could only be produced at disproportionate cost.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-13T12:37:50.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685407/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685407/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-06","National Insurance Contributions: Care Leavers","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will estimate the cost to the public purse of abolishing employer National Insurance contributions for care leavers in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Michael Gove","Surrey Heath","Michael Gove","63172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685408","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-09","<p>The information requested is not held.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-09T16:04:49.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685408/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685408/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-06","VAT: Take-away Food","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate has he made of the amount of VAT that has been raised in respect of hot takeaway food in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","63145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685409","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-09","<p>PQ 63121:</p><p> </p><p>Corporation Tax</p><p> </p><p>The number of incorporated businesses claiming Capital Allowances for Corporation Tax are as follows (rounded to the nearest 10,000):</p><p> </p><p>2013-14: 940,000</p><p>2014-15: 960,000</p><p> </p><p>Income Tax</p><p> </p><p>The number of individuals/unincorporated businesses within the income tax self-assessment system claiming Capital Allowances are as follows (rounded to the nearest 10,000):</p><p> </p><p>2013-14: 1,490,000</p><p>2014-15: 1,420,000</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>PQ 63125:</p><p> </p><p>Corporation Tax</p><p> </p><p>The number of incorporated businesses claiming the Annual Investment Allowance for Corporation Tax are as follows (rounded to the nearest 10,000):</p><p> </p><p>2013-14: 610,000</p><p>2014-15: 650,000</p><p> </p><p>Income Tax</p><p> </p><p>The number of individuals/unincorporated businesses within the income tax self-assessment system claiming the Annual Investment Allowance are as follows (rounded to the nearest 10,000):</p><p> </p><p>2013-14: 615,000</p><p>2014-15: 605,000</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>PQ 63129: Information is not held detailing how many people and businesses benefit from rollover relief for balancing charges on ships.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>PQ 63133:</p><p> </p><p>Corporation Tax</p><p> </p><p>The number of incorporated businesses claiming the Business Premises Renovation Allowance for Corporation Tax are as follows (rounded to the nearest 50):</p><p> </p><p>2013-14: 250</p><p>2014-15: 350</p><p> </p><p>Income Tax</p><p> </p><p>The number of individuals/unincorporated businesses within the income tax self-assessment system claiming the Business Premises Renovation Allowance are as follows (rounded to the nearest 50):</p><p> </p><p>2013-14: 1,150</p><p>2014-15: 1,000</p><p> </p><p>PQ 63147: In 2013-14 85 groups elected to use Tonnage Tax. Data is presented at a group level as companies elect into the Tonnage Tax scheme as a group of companies. 2014-15 data is currently unavailable and will only be made available from Autumn 2017.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","63121 ; 63125 ; 63129 ; 63133","2017-02-09T16:03:21.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685409/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685409/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-06","Tonnage Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many businesses elected to use tonnage tax in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","63147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685410","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-13","<p>Estimates of the cost of tax reliefs claimed against Petroleum Revenue Tax and Offshore (North Sea) Corporation Tax, arising from the production and extraction of North Sea oil and gas from the UK and UK Continental Shelf, are presented in HM Revenue and Customs’ tax relief publication, in the following two tables (latest versions December 2016):</p><p> </p><p>Main reliefs:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/579720/Dec_16_Main_Reliefs_Final.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/579720/Dec_16_Main_Reliefs_Final.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Minor reliefs:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/579993/Dec_16_Minor_Reliefs_Final.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/579993/Dec_16_Minor_Reliefs_Final.pdf</a></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-13T13:57:50.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685410/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685410/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-06","Fossil Fuels: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the financial value to fossil fuel producers of tax allowances taken up in financial year 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","63180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685411","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-13","<p>The Government does not provide subsidies to fossil fuel production or consumption.</p><p> </p><p>The UK’s oil and gas ring-fence regime means that profits from oil and gas production are taxed at a higher rate of 40%, compared to 20% for other sectors. The regime for oil and gas does include allowances, such as the Investment Allowance, which are designed to ensure otherwise economic developments are not uncommercial. This allows oil and gas companies to claim tax relief when making large, upfront investments in new infrastructure. Even where income is covered by an allowance, those companies continue to pay tax on their profits at a minimum rate of 30%.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-13T12:46:48.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685411/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685411/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-06","Fossil Fuels: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the value is of the subsidies provided for the (a) production and (b) consumption of fossil fuels in the current financial year.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","63181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685412","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-13","<p>Details of the value of Child Trust Fund vouchers issued to children born between 1 September 2002 and 2 January 2011 can be found at Table 2 of HM Revenue and Customs’ <em>Child Trust Fund Statistical Report</em>: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/255886/statistical-report.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/255886/statistical-report.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>A breakdown of the annual cost of Child Trust Fund government payments is provided at Table 6 of the same document.</p><p> </p><p>The Statistical Report shows that there were approximately 6.1m Child Trust Fund accounts at 5 April 2012.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","63197 ; 63198","2017-02-13T12:40:37.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685412/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685412/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-06","Child Trust Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the cost was of starting payment vouchers for child trust funds between 1 September 2002 and 2 January 2011.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","63196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685413","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-13","<p>Details of the value of Child Trust Fund vouchers issued to children born between 1 September 2002 and 2 January 2011 can be found at Table 2 of HM Revenue and Customs’ <em>Child Trust Fund Statistical Report</em>: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/255886/statistical-report.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/255886/statistical-report.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>A breakdown of the annual cost of Child Trust Fund government payments is provided at Table 6 of the same document.</p><p> </p><p>The Statistical Report shows that there were approximately 6.1m Child Trust Fund accounts at 5 April 2012.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","63196 ; 63198","2017-02-13T12:40:37.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685413/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685413/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-06","Child Trust Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many child trust funds exist.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","63197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685414","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-13","<p>Details of the value of Child Trust Fund vouchers issued to children born between 1 September 2002 and 2 January 2011 can be found at Table 2 of HM Revenue and Customs’ <em>Child Trust Fund Statistical Report</em>: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/255886/statistical-report.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/255886/statistical-report.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>A breakdown of the annual cost of Child Trust Fund government payments is provided at Table 6 of the same document.</p><p> </p><p>The Statistical Report shows that there were approximately 6.1m Child Trust Fund accounts at 5 April 2012.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","63196 ; 63197","2017-02-13T12:40:37.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685414/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685414/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-06","Child Trust Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the total cost has been of the child trust fund initiative.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","63198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685415","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-13","<p>The forecasted Exchequer revenues up to 2021-22 (Offshore Corporation Tax and Petroleum Revenue Tax) arising from the production and extraction of North Sea oil and gas from the UK and UK Continental Shelf are presented in Table 4.6 of the Office for Budget Responsibility’s (OBR’s) <em>Economic and Fiscal Outlook: November 2016</em>: <a href="http://cdn.budgetresponsibility.org.uk/Nov2016EFO.pdf" target="_blank">http://cdn.budgetresponsibility.org.uk/Nov2016EFO.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The OBR will be publishing updated forecasts on 8 March 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Longer term estimates of revenues from the production and extraction of North Sea oil and gas were published as a supplementary table of the OBR’s <em>Fiscal Sustainability Report: June 2015</em>: <a href="http://budgetresponsibility.org.uk/docs/dlm_uploads/FSR_2015_Supplementary_Tables.xlsx" target="_blank">http://budgetresponsibility.org.uk/docs/dlm_uploads/FSR_2015_Supplementary_Tables.xlsx</a></p><p> </p><p>It should be noted that the longer-term estimates are based on the March 2015 forecast and determinants.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-13T12:42:54.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685415/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685415/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685415/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-06","Offshore Industry: Tax Yields","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of annual future tax revenues from the North Sea oil and gas industry up to 2030.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","63182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685416","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-13","<p>Corporation Tax</p><p>For incorporated businesses, Landlord's Energy Saving Allowance is considered to be an allowable business expenditure and claimed as part of trading profit or loss calculations. Since corporation tax returns do not contain a breakdown of allowable business expenses, it is not possible to identify Landlord's Energy Saving Allowance claimed by incorporated property businesses from their tax returns.</p><p> </p><p>Income tax</p><p>The numbers of individuals/unincorporated businesses within the income tax self-assessment system who benefited from the Landlord's Energy Saving Allowance are as follows (rounded to the nearest 100).</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>6,100</p></td><td><p>5,800</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-13T12:13:31.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685416/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685416/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685416/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-06","Energy: Private Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) people and (b) businesses received the Landlord's Energy Saving Allowance in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","63120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685417","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-09","<p>PQ 63121:</p><p> </p><p>Corporation Tax</p><p> </p><p>The number of incorporated businesses claiming Capital Allowances for Corporation Tax are as follows (rounded to the nearest 10,000):</p><p> </p><p>2013-14: 940,000</p><p>2014-15: 960,000</p><p> </p><p>Income Tax</p><p> </p><p>The number of individuals/unincorporated businesses within the income tax self-assessment system claiming Capital Allowances are as follows (rounded to the nearest 10,000):</p><p> </p><p>2013-14: 1,490,000</p><p>2014-15: 1,420,000</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>PQ 63125:</p><p> </p><p>Corporation Tax</p><p> </p><p>The number of incorporated businesses claiming the Annual Investment Allowance for Corporation Tax are as follows (rounded to the nearest 10,000):</p><p> </p><p>2013-14: 610,000</p><p>2014-15: 650,000</p><p> </p><p>Income Tax</p><p> </p><p>The number of individuals/unincorporated businesses within the income tax self-assessment system claiming the Annual Investment Allowance are as follows (rounded to the nearest 10,000):</p><p> </p><p>2013-14: 615,000</p><p>2014-15: 605,000</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>PQ 63129: Information is not held detailing how many people and businesses benefit from rollover relief for balancing charges on ships.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>PQ 63133:</p><p> </p><p>Corporation Tax</p><p> </p><p>The number of incorporated businesses claiming the Business Premises Renovation Allowance for Corporation Tax are as follows (rounded to the nearest 50):</p><p> </p><p>2013-14: 250</p><p>2014-15: 350</p><p> </p><p>Income Tax</p><p> </p><p>The number of individuals/unincorporated businesses within the income tax self-assessment system claiming the Business Premises Renovation Allowance are as follows (rounded to the nearest 50):</p><p> </p><p>2013-14: 1,150</p><p>2014-15: 1,000</p><p> </p><p>PQ 63147: In 2013-14 85 groups elected to use Tonnage Tax. Data is presented at a group level as companies elect into the Tonnage Tax scheme as a group of companies. 2014-15 data is currently unavailable and will only be made available from Autumn 2017.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","63125 ; 63129 ; 63133 ; 63147","2017-02-09T16:03:21.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685417/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685417/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685417/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-06","Capital Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) people and (b) businesses received capital allowance in (i) 2013-14 and (ii) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","63121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685418","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-13","<p>The information is not held. HM Revenue and Customs bases its published relief values on expenditure amounts supplied by other Departments but does not collect information on the number of people receiving the allowances.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-13T12:36:48.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685418/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685418/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-06","Income Tax: Overseas Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people received income tax exemption of foreign service allowance paid to Crown servants abroad in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","63122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685419","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-13","<p>HM Revenue and Customs publishes the estimated cost of the income tax exemption of Premium Bond prizes here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/main-tax-expenditures-and-structural-reliefs" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/main-tax-expenditures-and-structural-reliefs</a>.</p><p>In 2013-14 and 2014-15 the cost of this exemption was estimated to be £130 million in each year.</p><p> </p><p>For this relief, estimates of the number of individuals benefitting are not held. The estimated costs are based on aggregate figures or assumptions.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-13T12:33:21.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685419/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685419/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685419/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-06","Premium Bonds: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people received income tax exemption of premium bond prizes in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","63124"
